DIGEST: BOXING TO RETURN TO HOTEL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIKE HISERMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Grand Ballroom of the Warner Center Marriott in Woodland Hills will be the 
site of a second boxing show, Nov. 23, starting at 7:30 p.m., organizers 
announced Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
 Boxing's debut one week ago in the upscale West Valley was marred by confusion 
stemming from a late change in the seating configuration inside the hotel's 
venue.The fire department requested the elimination of about 140 of 1,344 seats 
after a last-minute safety inspection. 
</P>
<P>
 As a result, boxing action was delayed twice -- for a total of about 40 
minutes -- and refunds were distributed to about 300 fans. 
</P>
<P>
 Fight promoter Peter Broudy said revised plans for a 1,088-seat venue were 
approved by hotel management and the fire marshall on Monday. "No one will feel 
the difference," Broudy said. "There's all kinds of aisles. It's perfect." MIKE 
HISERMAN 
