<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: SIMI VALLEY; HOMEMADE BOMB SHATTERS WINDSHIELD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MACK REED 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A homemade bomb shattered the early morning calm and a construction worker's 
windshield in Simi Valley on Tuesday, but injured no one at the home where it 
exploded, police said. 
</P>
<P>
 Someone packed a small aluminum tube with explosive material, taped BBs to it 
and placed it on a white Ford Ranger pickup truck owned by Richard Diaz, 28, 
said Simi Valley Police Detective Roger Meffan. 
</P>
<P>
 The bomb went off about 5 a.m., damaging the truck and embedding shrapnel up 
to one-inch deep in the plywood door of the garage the truck was facing, Meffan 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 "If anyone was within 10 or 15 feet of it, it would have caused serious 
injury," the detective said. 
</P>
<P>
 Diaz was asleep on the other side of house, and called police after the blast 
woke him, Meffan said. 
</P>
<P>
 Police say the bombing could have stemmed from a dispute between Meffan and a 
neighbor, but they are still trying to establish a clear motive for the attack. 
MACK REED 
</P>
