<HEADLINE>
<P>
SHORTY ROGERS, 70; JAZZ TRUMPETER AND COMPOSER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Shorty Rogers, a trumpeter, composer and arranger who was one of the leading 
figures in the West Coast jazz scene of the early 1950s, died on Monday in Los 
Angeles. He was 70. 
</P>
<P>
 Born Milton M. Rajonsky in Great Barrington, Mass., Rogers performed with the 
Woody Herman band in the late 1940s, and in 1950-51 he composed several 
important works for the Stan Kenton band. 
</P>
<P>
 After settling on the West Coast he led his own small ensembles and big bands 
before becoming active in film music, supervising the scoring for "The Wild 
One" (1953) and "The Man With the Golden Arm" (1955). 
</P>
<P>
 Rogers was a pioneer in the jazz exploration of such contemporary music 
techniques as bitonality, modal improvisation and 12-tone composition, and one 
of the first trumpeters to regularly use the fluegelhorn. He worked primarily 
in film and television studios after the early 1960s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
