<HEADLINE>
<P>
BANKERS TO STUDY OFFER FOR ROPAK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Ropak Corp., a major manufacturer of plastic shipping containers, said Tuesday 
that a special directors committee has hired an investment banking firm to 
evaluate a $53-million bid for the company. 
</P>
<P>
 The committee of three outside directors retained Wertheim Schroder & Co. Inc. 
in New York to review the cash offer of $10.50 a share from Linpac Mouldings 
Ltd. in Birmingham, England, and determine if it is fair to minority 
shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
 The Roper family, which controls 25.4% of the stock, favors the sale of the 
company. Linpac owns 8.5%. 
</P>
<P>
 Ronald W. Cameron, a Ropak executive, said the acquisition price would be 
worth $80 million because Linpac would pay $53 million for the stock it doesn't 
own and assume about $27 million in Ropak debt. 
</P>
<P>
 Ropak shares were up 12.5 cents Tuesday to close at $10.25 in Nasdaq trading. 
</P>
